In a significant legal development, a federal jury in California has found Meta Platforms Inc. liable for violating the California Invasion of Privacy Act by collecting sensitive health data from users of the Flo period-tracking app without their consent. The lawsuit, initiated in 2021, accused Flo Health Inc. of sharing users' intimate health information, including menstrual cycles and fertility goals, with Meta through embedded software development kits (SDKs) between 2016 and 2019. While Flo, Google, and analytics firm Flurry settled the case earlier, Meta chose to proceed to trial and has indicated plans to appeal the verdict.
